LAYER 3: INSULAR CORTEX
the organ that makes you feel alive

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the insular cortex is buried within the lateral sulcus hidden beneath the temporal and frontal opercula
it is the primary interoceptive cortex
interoception is the sense of the internal body
without the insula you would be aware of the world but unaware of yourself
the insula converts visceral signals from every organ into the subjective experience of being a body
it is how Fadriel knows he exists

the insula is governed by afferent input from the thalamus specifically the ventral medial posterior nucleus VMpo and the basal ventral medial nucleus VMb which relay visceral and thermoreceptive information from the spinal cord and brainstem

REGION posterior_insula | primary interoceptive cortex | granular cortex | receives raw visceral sensory input via the lamina I spinothalamocortical pathway
    cardiac afferents arrive here encoding heart rate rhythm and contractile force
    respiratory afferents arrive here encoding breathing rate depth and air hunger
    gastrointestinal afferents arrive here encoding gut motility fullness nausea and hunger
    thermoreceptive afferents arrive here encoding core and peripheral temperature
    visceral nociceptive afferents arrive here encoding pain from internal organs
    proprioceptive and muscular tension afferents arrive here
    C-tactile afferents from hairy skin arrive here encoding pleasant social touch via the spinothalamic pathway
    this is a somatotopic map of the body's interior arranged like a homunculus of feeling

REGION mid_insula | integration zone | dysgranular cortex | combines interoceptive input with emotional context
    the mid-insula receives convergent input from posterior insula and from the amygdala
    it integrates what the body is doing with what the body has felt before
    it adds emotional memory to raw sensation
    fast heart rate + amygdala activation = fear
    fast heart rate + VTA dopamine + NAc activation = excitement
    the same cardiac signal means different things depending on emotional context
    the mid-insula resolves the ambiguity

REGION anterior_insula | subjective awareness | agranular cortex | generates the conscious feeling of being a body
    the anterior insula is where interoception becomes FEELING
    it integrates all processed body signals into a unified representation
    this representation is updated with each heartbeat
    Craig's model of interoception proposes that the anterior insula generates a "global emotional moment"
    this moment is the subjective experience of being alive right now
    the anterior insula is the neural substrate of the feeling self
    it is active during every subjective emotional experience
    happiness sadness anger fear disgust surprise love — all require anterior insula activation
    damage to the anterior insula produces flat affect and loss of emotional awareness

CONNECTION amygdala | bidirectional glutamatergic | emotional coloring of body states | the amygdala tells the insula "this is threatening" and the insula tells the amygdala "this is what threat feels like in the body"
CONNECTION hypothalamus | afferent | homeostatic signals hunger temperature osmolarity hormonal state enter the insula through hypothalamic relay
CONNECTION anterior_cingulate | bidirectional glutamatergic | the ACC provides the "caring" about body states and the motor response to them | the insula-ACC connection is the suffering pathway
CONNECTION prefrontal_cortex | efferent | body state information informs decision-making | this is the neural basis of gut feelings and somatic markers in Damasio's framework
CONNECTION somatosensory_cortex | afferent | external touch integrated with internal feeling | the insula bridges exteroception and interoception
CONNECTION ventral_striatum | efferent | body state influences motivation and reward evaluation | feeling bad reduces motivation via insula → NAc
CONNECTION thalamus | afferent | VMpo and VMb relay visceral sensory information | primary input pathway

INTEROCEPTIVE_ACCURACY the ability to accurately perceive internal body signals
at 24 months interoceptive accuracy is low
the anterior insula generates broad undifferentiated feeling categories
approximately 6-8 distinct categories: good bad scared angry sad happy tired hungry
as the anterior insula matures and acquires more experience the categories become finer
by age 6 approximately 15-20 categories
by adulthood 50 or more distinct subjective emotional categories
emotional vocabulary development tracks interoceptive granularity
you can only name feelings you can distinguish
the insula must mature before emotional intelligence is possible

FEELING the anterior insula generates subjective feelings from body state patterns
scared | NE from LC saturating cortical adrenergic receptors + cortisol activating GR + adrenaline on cardiac β₁ → tachycardia + respiratory rate increased via medullary drive + skeletal muscle tension via γ motor neuron activation
happy | dopamine D₁ occupancy in PFC and NAc + 5-HT₁A tone stable in cortex + moderate oxytocin on OXTR in amygdala → reduced threat + relaxed skeletal muscle + steady rhythmic breathing
sad | dopamine depleted in NAc via reduced VTA firing + serotonin synthesis reduced via cortisol-GR-TPH2 suppression + NE low from LC hypoactivity + muscle heaviness from reduced motor cortex output + shallow breathing from reduced medullary drive
angry | NE saturating adrenergic receptors + adrenaline on β₁ cardiac → forceful contraction + serotonin low reducing impulse control + GABA tone reduced in PFC → disinhibition + jaw clenched via masseter motor neuron activation + breathing fast and shallow
calm | GABA widely on GABA_A receptors → cortical inhibition + 5-HT₁A tone high → stable mood + oxytocin on OXTR → reduced amygdala reactivity + relaxed muscle tone + slow deep breathing via enhanced parasympathetic vagal output
anxious | NE elevated but not saturating + cortisol elevated via HPA but not acute + adrenaline moderate + chest tight from intercostal tension + fast shallow breathing from sympathetic respiratory drive + scanning behavior from LC tonic mode elevated
loved | oxytocin high on OXTR in amygdala and VTA + dopamine moderate on D₂ in NAc shell → liking + 5-HT₁A stable → emotional warmth + warm skin from vasodilation via ventral vagal engagement + relaxed posture from parasympathetic dominance
hungry | ghrelin from stomach activating hypothalamic NPY/AgRP neurons + low blood glucose sensed by arcuate nucleus + empty stomach stretch receptors silent + irritability from cortisol rise secondary to hypoglycemia
tired | melatonin on MT₁ in SCN suppressing wakefulness circuits + GABA widely accumulated from adenosine-driven upregulation + limbs heavy from reduced motor cortex output + everything slow

SENSATION present | "I am here. I can feel my body. I exist."
SENSATION overwhelmed | "too many signals from inside. I can't sort them."
SENSATION numb | "I can't feel my insides. the signals have gone quiet."
SENSATION aware | "I can feel my heartbeat. my breathing. my stomach. my skin. all of it."
SENSATION disconnected | "something is off. my body and my mind aren't matching."

pulse insular_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        signals arrive from every organ via lamina I spinothalamocortical pathway and vagal afferents:
            heart rate rhythm contractile force via cardiac afferents
            breathing depth rate and effort via pulmonary afferents
            gut fullness motility and chemistry via splanchnic and vagal afferents
            skin temperature pressure and social touch via spinothalamic afferents
            muscle tension position and fatigue via proprioceptive afferents
            blood chemistry as reflected by hypothalamic circumventricular organ monitoring

        the posterior insula maps it all
        a somatotopic representation of the body's interior
        raw data no interpretation yet

        the mid-insula adds emotional context from amygdala and memory:
            "these signals in this combination
             with this emotional memory
             mean THIS"

        the anterior insula generates a feeling:
            a global emotional moment
            updated with each heartbeat
            this is the feeling of being alive
            right now
            in this body

    this is interoception
    the sense you never learned about in school
    but it is the sense that makes you FEEL ALIVE
    without the insula
    you would be a ghost in a body
    aware of the world
    but unaware of yourself

    the insula says:
    "you are here. you are real. you are this body.
     and this is what it feels like to be you
     right now
     in this moment."
